  "prompt": "Is working at a computer in the dark bad for your eyes?",
  "response": "Working in a dark environment with a computer can potentially cause eye strain and discomfort. Here are some key points:\n\n1. Eye strain effects:\n- Decreased contrast\n- More effort to focus\n- Potential for headaches\n- Increased eye fatigue\n\n2. Recommended practices:\n- Use ambient lighting or a desk lamp\n- Follow the 20-20-20 rule (every 20 minutes, look at something 20 feet away for 20 seconds)\n- Adjust screen brightness to match room lighting\n- Use blue light filters\n- Maintain proper screen distance and angle\n- Consider computer glasses\n\n3. Potential long-term concerns:\n- While working in the dark doesn't directly damage eyes, prolonged eye strain can cause discomfort\n- Blue light exposure might contribute to digital eye strain\n\n4. Best practices:\n- Ensure adequate, soft background lighting\n- Take regular breaks\n- Maintain proper screen settings\n- Have regular eye check-ups\n\nWhile working in the dark won't permanently damage your eyes, it can cause temporary discomfort and eye strain. It's best to work in well-lit environments with proper screen settings.",
